            Title = "Time Tracking Overview",
            Slug = "time-tracking-overview",
            Summary = "What time tracking does, how timers and manual entries work, clock events, job linking, and how time data connects to payroll and costing.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 1,
            AppRoutes = """["/time-tracking"]""",
            Tags = """["time-tracking","timers"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Time Tracking Overview\n\nThe Time Tracking module records how employees spend their working hours. It supports two methods of capturing time — live timers and manual entries — and integrates with clock events, jobs, payroll, and cost accounting.\n\n### Two Ways to Track Time\n\n**Live Timers:** Click Start Timer to begin tracking time in real time. The timer runs until you click Stop Timer. The elapsed duration is calculated automatically from the start and stop timestamps. Timers sync across browser tabs and devices in real time — if you start a timer on your phone, your desktop shows it running immediately.\n\n**Manual Entries:** Click Manual Entry to log time after the fact. You enter the date, hours, minutes, an optional category, and optional notes. Manual entries are marked with a pencil icon in the table to distinguish them from timer-based entries.\n\n### Categories\n\nEvery time entry (timer or manual) can be tagged with a category:\n- **Production** — direct production work on a job\n- **Setup** — machine setup, tooling changes, fixture preparation\n- **Inspection** — quality checks, measurements, first-article inspection\n- **Maintenance** — equipment maintenance, cleaning, calibration\n- **Training** — learning, onboarding, skill development\n- **Meeting** — team meetings, planning sessions, standups\n- **Admin** — paperwork, emails, administrative tasks\n- **Cleanup** — end-of-shift cleanup, organizing\n- **Other** — anything that doesn't fit the above\n\nCategories are optional but recommended — they feed into reports and help managers understand how time is distributed across activities.\n\n### Clock Events\n\nClock events are separate from time entries. They record when an employee clocks in or out of the facility using an RFID badge, barcode scan, or manual entry on the shop floor kiosk. Clock events track:\n- **Event type** — clock-in, clock-out, break-start, break-end (driven by reference data)\n- **Timestamp** — when the event occurred\n- **Scan method** — how the employee identified themselves (RFID, barcode, manual)\n- **Source** — which device or kiosk recorded the event\n- **Reason** — optional note (e.g., 'early departure — appointment')\n\nClock events establish the employee's presence on-site. Time entries track what they worked on during that presence.\n\n### Job Linking\n\nTime entries can be linked to a specific job. When a timer is started from a job's detail panel on the kanban board, the job association is set automatically. This connects time directly to job costing — the labor cost for each entry is calculated from the employee's rate and applied to the job's cost rollup.\n\n### Date Range Filtering\n\nThe time tracking page has From and To date pickers that filter the entries table. A summary line shows the total hours and entry count for the current filter. When no dates are set, recent entries are shown.\n\n### Locking and Editability\n\nTime entries can be locked by a manager or by pay period closure. Locked entries show a lock icon and cannot be edited or deleted. Unlocked entries from today or future dates can be deleted; past entries require an admin time correction (which creates an audit trail).\n\n### Admin Time Corrections\n\nManagers and admins can correct time entries via the Admin > Time Corrections page. Corrections require a reason and are saved to an audit trail that preserves the original values. Fields that can be corrected include date, duration, start/end times, category, notes, and job assignment.\n\n### Pay Periods and Overtime\n\nTime entries roll up into pay periods (weekly, bi-weekly, semi-monthly, or monthly — configurable in admin settings). When a pay period is locked, all entries within that period become read-only. Overtime rules can be configured (e.g., >40 hours/week = 1.5x) and the system calculates overtime breakdowns per employee per week.\n\n### Real-Time Sync\n\nTimer start and stop events sync instantly. If two browser tabs are open, starting a timer in one tab updates the other tab's display immediately. The button at the top of the page switches between Start Timer and Stop Timer based on whether a timer is currently active.\n\n### Connection to Payroll\n\nTime entries feed into payroll calculations. Each entry's labor cost is computed from the employee's hourly rate multiplied by the duration. Overhead cost is tracked separately. When QuickBooks integration is active, time entries can sync to the accounting system as time activities.","sections":[]}"""
