            ContentJson = """{"passingScore":80,"questionsPerQuiz":8,"shuffleOptions":true,"showExplanationsAfterSubmit":true,"questions":[{"id":"tt1","text":"You need to track time for a 2-hour machine setup that happened yesterday. What is the correct approach?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Start a timer now and stop it after 2 hours"},{"id":"b","text":"Click Manual Entry, set the date to yesterday, enter 2 hours and 0 minutes, and select the Setup category","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Ask your manager to add it via the Admin panel"},{"id":"d","text":"Create a clock event with type 'setup' and a 2-hour duration"}],"explanation":"Manual entries are for logging time after the fact. Set the date to when the work was done, enter the duration in hours and minutes, and optionally select a category. Timer entries are for real-time tracking only."},{"id":"tt2","text":"You started a timer 45 minutes ago and need to stop it. Where do you find the stop button?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"In the same location as the Start Timer button — it changes to Stop Timer when a timer is running","isCorrect":true},{"id":"b","text":"Right-click the active timer row in the table and select Stop"},{"id":"c","text":"Open the manual entry dialog and click Stop Active Timer"},{"id":"d","text":"Navigate to Admin > Time Tracking > Active Timers"}],"explanation":"The Start Timer button in the page header dynamically changes to a Stop Timer button (with elapsed time displayed) whenever a timer is running. Click it to open the stop dialog."},{"id":"tt3","text":"What is the difference between a time entry and a clock event?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"They are the same thing — clock events are just time entries from the shop floor"},{"id":"b","text":"Time entries record what work was done and for how long; clock events record when an employee arrived at or left the facility","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Clock events track machine uptime; time entries track human labor"},{"id":"d","text":"Time entries are for salaried employees; clock events are for hourly workers"}],"explanation":"Time entries track work duration and can be linked to jobs and categories. Clock events track facility presence — when someone clocked in, clocked out, or took breaks. They serve different purposes but complement each other."},{"id":"tt4","text":"A time entry in the table shows a lock icon instead of a delete button. What does this mean?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The entry is linked to a job and cannot be modified without unlinking it first"},{"id":"b","text":"The entry is either locked by a manager/pay period or is a past-date entry that requires an admin correction to change","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The entry has been synced to QuickBooks and is waiting for confirmation"},{"id":"d","text":"The entry belongs to another user and you don't have permission to delete it"}],"explanation":"The lock icon appears when an entry is locked (by a manager or pay period closure) or when it's a past-date entry. Only today's or future unlocked entries can be deleted directly. Past entries require an admin time correction."},{"id":"tt5","text":"You want to see only the time entries from the first week of March. How do you filter the table?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Type '03/01' into the search box in the page header"},{"id":"b","text":"Set the From date to 03/01 and the To date to 03/07 using the date pickers in the filter bar","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Click the Date column header and select the date range from the dropdown"},{"id":"d","text":"Go to Reports > Time Report and set the date range there"}],"explanation":"The filter bar has From and To date pickers. Set From to the start date and To to the end date. The table and summary line update automatically to show only entries within that range."},{"id":"tt6","text":"An active timer entry shows 'Running' in green in the Duration column. What happens if you close the browser and reopen the time tracking page?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The timer is lost — you need to manually add the time"},{"id":"b","text":"The timer is still running because the start time is saved on the server; the elapsed time is figured from that saved start time","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The timer pauses and you can resume it from where you left off"},{"id":"d","text":"The timer stops automatically and a manual entry is created for the elapsed time"}],"explanation":"Timers live on the server. The start time is saved when you click Start, and the length is worked out from that time when you stop. Closing the browser doesn't affect the running timer — it keeps tracking from the saved start time."},{"id":"tt7","text":"You started a timer on your laptop. Will it show as running on your phone's browser too?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"No — timers are per-device and per-session"},{"id":"b","text":"Yes — timer changes sync to every device you're signed in on in real time","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Only if you manually refresh the page on your phone"},{"id":"d","text":"Only if both devices are on the same network"}],"explanation":"Starting or stopping a timer syncs to all your open tabs and devices in real time. When you start a timer on any device, the button at the top switches from Start Timer to Stop Timer everywhere automatically."},{"id":"tt8","text":"A manager needs to correct a time entry from last week that has the wrong duration. What is the proper process?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Delete the entry and create a new one with the correct duration"},{"id":"b","text":"Use Admin > Time Corrections, select the entry, change the duration, and provide a reason for the correction","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Edit the entry directly in the data table by double-clicking the duration cell"},{"id":"d","text":"Ask the employee to submit a new manual entry with the correct hours"}],"explanation":"Admin time corrections preserve an audit trail. The manager enters the corrected values and a required reason. The original values are kept in the audit trail so there is a complete record of what changed and why."},{"id":"tt9","text":"What categories are available when starting a timer or creating a manual entry?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Only Production and Setup — other categories must be created in Admin settings"},{"id":"b","text":"None, Production, Setup, Inspection, Maintenance, Training, Meeting, Admin, Cleanup, and Other","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Categories are not available for timers, only for manual entries"},{"id":"d","text":"The category list is custom per company — there are no default categories"}],"explanation":"Both timer and manual entry dialogs offer the same category dropdown: None (default), Production, Setup, Inspection, Maintenance, Training, Meeting, Admin, Cleanup, and Other. Categories are optional but help with reporting."},{"id":"tt10","text":"How is a time entry linked to a job for cost tracking?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"You must manually type the job number into the notes field"},{"id":"b","text":"A time entry can be tied to a job — when you start a timer from a job's detail panel on the kanban board, the link is set for you","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Jobs are linked after the fact by running a batch report in Admin"},{"id":"d","text":"All time entries are automatically linked to whatever job is currently selected on the kanban board"}],"explanation":"A time entry can optionally be tied to a job. When you start a timer from a specific job's detail panel, the link is set for you. The linked job number appears in the Job column, and the labor cost lands on that job."},{"id":"tt11","text":"The summary line below the date filters shows '8.5 hours across 12 entries'. You change the From date to yesterday. What happens?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Nothing — the summary only updates when you click a Refresh button"},{"id":"b","text":"The table reloads with the new date filter applied and the summary line updates to reflect the filtered results","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The summary line stays the same but the table filters to show only yesterday's entries"},{"id":"d","text":"A confirmation dialog asks whether to apply the new filter"}],"explanation":"The date filter controls trigger an automatic reload of the entries table whenever their value changes. The summary line recalculates from the filtered entries, showing the new total hours and count."},{"id":"tt12","text":"What does the 'Type' column badge tell you about a time entry?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Whether the entry is billable (blue) or non-billable (gray)"},{"id":"b","text":"Whether the entry was created via a live timer ('Timer' badge, teal) or logged after the fact ('Manual' badge, gray)","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The entry's priority level — high (blue) or normal (gray)"},{"id":"d","text":"Whether the entry has been approved by a manager (blue) or is pending (gray)"}],"explanation":"The Type badge distinguishes how the time was recorded. 'Timer' (teal) means it was tracked via the Start/Stop Timer feature with precise timestamps. 'Manual' (gray) means it was entered by the user after the work was done with a specified duration."}]}"""
